ng book, Ignacio Palacios-Huerta illuminates economics through the world's most popular sport. He offers unique and often startling insights into game theory and microeconomics, covering topics such as mixed strategies, discrimination, incentives, and human preferences. He also looks at finance, experimental economics, behavioral economics, and neuroeconomics. Soccer provides rich data sets and environments that shed light on universal economic principles in interesting and useful ways.Essential reading for students, researchers, and sports enthusiasts, Beautiful Game Theory is the first book to show what soccer can do for economics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEconomicsxPsychological aspects. 0aGame theory. 0aSoccerxEconomic aspects. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / Theory.2bisacsh  aArgentina.  aEnglish league soccer.  aJohn F. Nash Jr.  abehavioral bias.  abehavioral changes.  abrain.  acompetition.  acompetitive games.  acorruption.  acriminal damage.  adiscrimination.  aeconomics.  aefficient-markets hypothesis.  aemotional response.  aequilibrium concept.  aexperimental design.  aexperimental economics.  agame theory.  ahalftime.  ahooliganism.  ahuman behavior.  ahuman preference.  aincentives.  alaboratory experiment.  amicroeconomics.  aminimax theorem.  amixed strategies.  aneuroeconomics.  aneurophysiology.  apenalty kick game.  apenalty kick.  apenalty kicks.  apenalty shoot-out.  apenalty shoot-outs.  aprejudice.  aprobability mixtures.  aprofessional athletes.  aprofessional soccer players.  apsychological bias.  apsychological pressure.  areferee bias.  arewards.  ascoring.  asoccer fans.  asoccer games.  asoccer players.  asoccer.  asocial forces.  asocial pressure.  asport.  asports fan